{
  "doc_id": "29909",
  "text": "Numerous studies have taken more of an empirical approach to this issue by observing the effects of varying m and r on the calculated MSE results. In our systematic review, Duarte et al. [CITATION_1] and Jiang et al. [CITATION_2] performed such evaluations and have concluded that while absolute changes in complexity values are observed, relative changes were insignificant [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Indeed, according to Duarte et al., the relative results remain generally consistent when r is swept between 10% and 30% [CITATION_5] , suggesting that this range should be sufficient for most data sets. Similarly, Pincus et al., has found that entropy analyses produce statistically reliable and reproducible results with m = 2 and r = 10%-25% and an appropriate data length [CITATION_6] . Our systematic review reveals that the selection of m and r are relatively consistent across studies: sequence length m is typically 2 and point matching tolerance r is either 15% or 20%.",
